<Document>
<name>Hai Van Pass — Hue to Hoi An</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Hai Van Pass — Hue to Hoi An</h2><p><i>Central Vietnam · Hue to Hoi An via Lang Co and Da Nang</i></p><p><b>Top Gear's 'one of the best coast roads in the world' — Vietnam's south-vs-north climate dividing line.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>111 km (69 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs no stops; full day with</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>February–August (autumn–winter brings cloud and rain to the pass)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Tour buses; truck traffic uses the tunnel beneath now, but motorbikes and cars share the pass road; rain reduces visibility; landslides in storm season</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>272</td></tr></table><hr><p>Hai Van means 'Sea Cloud Pass' — the 496 m gap in the Annamite mountains where they fall into the South China Sea. The pass is the climate divider between northern and southern Vietnam: stand on the summit and in winter the north is grey and cool, the south is bright and warm. The road over the top was bypassed in 2005 by a 6.3 km tunnel; trucks and buses now go through, leaving the pass road blissfully quiet. Fortified by the Nguyen dynasty in the 19th century and by the French and Americans in the 20th, the summit has concrete bunkers among the souvenir shops. Continue south through Da Nang (American base in the war, now a beach city) to the lantern-lit old port of Hoi An (UNESCO), preserved 17th-century houses still in use.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Hue Imperial City</b> — Citadel of the Nguyen dynasty (1802–1945), UNESCO. The Forbidden Purple City inside was largely destroyed in the 1968 Tet Offensive; restoration is ongoing. Perfume River boat tours to royal tombs upstream.</li><li><b>Lang Co</b> — Long curve of pale beach between lagoon and ocean. Best photo of the pass curling up the headland behind. Restaurants on stilts over the lagoon serve oysters straight from the water.</li><li><b>Hai Van Pass summit</b> — 496 m. Hai Van Quan ('Sea Cloud Gate') is a Nguyen-era stone fortress at the saddle. Bunkers on either side from US Army occupation. Look back north for the long curve down to Lang Co; south to Da Nang Bay.</li><li><b>Da Nang / Dragon Bridge</b> — 666 m steel bridge in the form of a dragon over the Han River. Breathes fire and sprays water at 9 PM Saturdays and Sundays. China Beach (My Khe) is the old American R&amp;R beach.</li><li><b>Marble Mountains</b> — Five limestone hills with caves and Buddhist shrines inside. Climb 156 steps up Thuy Son or take the elevator. The marble was carted off to make tombstones for over a century; now extraction is banned.</li><li><b>Hoi An</b> — 16th-19th-century trading port frozen in time. Lantern festival on every full moon — power cut, the streets lit only by silk lanterns. Tailors will make a custom suit overnight.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
